knowledge_graph.description: A tortilla is a thin, circular unleavened flatbread from Mesoamerica originally made from maize hominy meal, and now also from wheat flour. The Aztecs and other Nahuatl speakers called tortillas tlaxcalli.

related_questions.question: Are tortillas healthier than bread?
related_questions.snippet: Which is healthier: bread or tortilla? Is bread more fattening than tortilla? Bread and corn tortillas have a very similar nutrient profile. However, if you are choosing a flour tortilla, to get the most health benefit, be sure to choose one made with whole-wheat flour rather than refined white flour.
related_questions.title: What's Better: Bread vs. Tortilla vs. Pita vs. Wrap? - Wildgrain

related_questions.question: Are tortillas Mexican or Spanish?
related_questions.snippet: If by tortillas you mean the corn flatbread used to make tacos, then they are Mexican. But if you mean the omelet-like dish made with eggs and potatoes (also known as “tortilla de patatas”), then we're talking about a Spanish specialty.
related_questions.title: Are Tortillas Mexican or Spanish? - El Pollo Norteño

related_questions.question: Are chapati and tortilla the same?
related_questions.snippet: Conclusion. Roti and tortillas are two types of flatbreads that originate from India. While they share a few similarities, a key difference sets them apart: roti is made with whole wheat flour, whereas tortillas are made with maize (corn) flour.
related_questions.title: What is the difference between Roti and Tortilla? - Masalabox

related_questions.question: What is a tortilla?
related_questions.snippet: tortilla, round, thin, flat bread of Mexico made from unleavened cornmeal or, less commonly, wheat flour. Traditionally, the corn (maize) for tortillas was boiled with unslaked lime to soften the kernels and loosen the hulls.
